Alright, I'm going to try to make a point really fast but before I do that, I want to apologize for getting upset before. I thought I was getting dismissive responses without being clear and that frustrated me, but I should have lashed out about it, so I am sorry.

Anyway, I was trying to approach the topic like I would when talking about security clearances. I don't trust someone I don't know and if someone I want to work with has a lot of contacts I don't know and therefore don't trust, I may not work with them as easily (especially when the thing I want to work with them on has a history of being leaked in the first place and then people complaining that my organization needs to "do better" with it) If the response of "what if"ing is that this is only "what if" they think like this, then I get that point and didn't originally. I thought it was being said that I was "what if"ing anything going wrong on our side and I wasn't because it doesn't matter; It's WOTC who has to worry about "what if" and I was just trying to paint their perspective on the topic. I'm not sure if that helps move forward in the situation, but I normally believe if you understand the other side's concerns / worries, you can communicate more clearly how you can mitigate those things. That was all I wanted to say.
